4b. FALSIFICATION
Falsification means manipulating or distorting actual research data, equipment, processes, or
results. Unlike fabrication (inventing nothing), falsification starts with real data but changes it to
produce a desired result.
Aspect Detail
Definition Manipulating existing data, images, or results to misrepresent findings
Example Removing outliers that don't support the hypothesis from the dataset
Example 2 Digitally altering microscopy images to show clearer results
Example 3 Changing p-value from 0.08 to 0.04 to make result 'significant'
Severity Very HIGH — distorts existing scientific record
Detection Comparison with raw data; image forensics; statistical review
