Fig. 6 — Timeline of Landmark Research Ethics Codes
7a. Nuremberg Code (1947)
The Nuremberg Code was the first international code of research ethics, developed in response to
the Nazi medical experiments revealed at the Nuremberg Trials. It established 10 principles for ethical
research on human subjects.
Principle Content
Principle 1 Voluntary consent of human subject is ABSOLUTELY ESSENTIAL — the most
famous principle
Principle 2 Experiment must yield fruitful results for the good of society
Principle 3 Based on prior animal experimentation and knowledge
Principle 4 Avoid unnecessary physical and mental suffering
Principle 5 No experiment should be conducted if there is reason to believe it will cause
death
Principle 6 Risk should never exceed humanitarian importance of the problem
Principle 7 Proper preparations and facilities to protect the subject
Principle 8 Only scientifically qualified persons may conduct the research
Principle 9 Subject must be free to stop participation at any time
Principle 10 Researcher must be prepared to terminate if harm is likely
7b. Declaration of Helsinki (1964)
The Declaration of Helsinki was adopted by the World Medical Association (WMA) in 1964
specifically for medical research involving human subjects. It has been revised multiple times
(most recently 2013) and is the cornerstone of medical research ethics worldwide.
