11. MCQ PRACTICE QUESTIONS (12
Questions)
UGC NET Paper 1 style — attempt each before reading the answer.
1. The MOST important principle of the Nuremberg Code is:
(A) Research must benefit society
(B) Voluntary consent of the human subject is absolutely essential n
(C) Research must be based on animal experiments first
(D) Only qualified scientists may conduct research
n: Explanation: Principle 1 of the Nuremberg Code states that 'the voluntary consent of
the human subject is absolutely essential.' This is the single most emphasised and
frequently tested principle of the Code.
2. The Belmont Report (1979) identified THREE core principles. Which of the
following is NOT one of them?
(A) Respect for Persons
(B) Beneficence
(C) Non-maleficence n
(D) Justice
n: Explanation: The Belmont Report's three principles are: Respect for Persons,
Beneficence, and Justice. Non-maleficence is a principle from biomedical ethics
(Beauchamp & Childress) but is NOT one of the three Belmont principles.
3. 'Fabrication' in research misconduct means:
(A) Manipulating existing data to change results
(B) Using someone else's ideas without credit
(C) Inventing data or results that were never collected n
(D) Publishing the same paper in two journals
n: Explanation: Fabrication = making up data. Falsification = changing existing data.
Plagiarism = taking others' work. Duplicate publication = submitting same paper to multiple
journals. The FFP Triad is Fabrication, Falsification, Plagiarism.
4. Which of the following offers STRONGER protection of participant identity?
(A) Confidentiality
(B) Anonymity n
(C) Pseudonymity
