(D) Disclosure
n: Explanation: Anonymity is stronger — the researcher never knows who the participant
is (no identity collected). Confidentiality means the researcher knows but promises
protection. Once identity is known, there is always a risk of breach.
5. 'HARKing' in research refers to:
(A) High-Accuracy Research Kinetics
(B) Hypothesising After Results are Known n
(C) Harmless Application of Research Knowledge
(D) Holistic Assessment of Research Kinetics
n: Explanation: HARKing = Hypothesising After Results are Known — the fraudulent
practice of presenting post-hoc (after-the-fact) hypotheses as if they were formulated
before data collection. It is a form of research misconduct.
6. The Declaration of Helsinki (1964) was adopted by:
(A) United Nations
(B) World Health Organization
(C) World Medical Association n
(D) American Psychological Association
n: Explanation: The Declaration of Helsinki was adopted by the World Medical
Association (WMA) — an international organization of physicians. It specifically governs
medical research involving human subjects.
7. In India, biomedical research ethics is governed by guidelines published by:
(A) UGC
(B) NCERT
(C) ICMR n
(D) DST
n: Explanation: ICMR (Indian Council of Medical Research) publishes the National
Ethical Guidelines for Biomedical and Health Research Involving Human Participants
(2017) — the primary ethics guideline for biomedical research in India.
8. The 3Rs framework in animal research stands for:
(A) Research, Results, Reporting
(B) Replacement, Reduction, Refinement n
(C) Review, Research, Regulate
(D) Rights, Responsibility, Respect
