n: Explanation: The 3Rs: Replacement (use alternatives instead of animals), Reduction
(use fewer animals), Refinement (minimise suffering). This framework is required by
CPCSEA in India and IACUC in the USA for all animal research.
9. Which case directly led to the development of the Belmont Report?
(A) Nazi Medical Experiments
(B) Thalidomide Tragedy
(C) Willowbrook Study
(D) Tuskegee Syphilis Study n
n: Explanation: The Tuskegee Syphilis Study (1932–1972), where Black men with
syphilis were deliberately left untreated, led directly to the National Commission and the
Belmont Report (1979). The Nazi experiments led to the Nuremberg Code (1947).
10. A researcher lists a senior professor as co-author who had no involvement in
the study. This is:
(A) Fabrication
(B) Ghost Authorship n
(C) Falsification
(D) Duplicate Publication
n: Explanation: Ghost authorship (or gift/guest authorship) = listing someone who made
no intellectual contribution as an author. It is a form of research misconduct. True
authorship requires: conception, design, data analysis, OR drafting the manuscript.
11. Institutional Review Board (IRB) reviews research BEFORE it begins to:
(A) Provide funding for the research
(B) Ensure findings are published in reputed journals
(C) Protect human subjects and ensure ethical standards are met n
(D) Review the statistical methods used
n: Explanation: IRB (called IEC in India) is an independent ethics committee that reviews
and approves research protocols BEFORE data collection begins. Its primary role is to
protect the rights and welfare of research participants.
12. Informed consent is considered INVALID when:
(A) Given in written form
(B) Given by a competent adult voluntarily
(C) Given under coercion or without full information n
(D) Given before the study begins
